that well-intentioned scientists and environmentalists originally crafted the jungle narrative with the primary goal of saving the world’s tropical rainforests from destruction. It was a strategy deployed to address a pressing environmental problem, one that appeared at a propitious point in history just as the Western world was taking a more globalized view of environmental issues. And yet, although supported by science and its practitioners, the story was also underpinned by a persuasive mix of myth, sentimentality, and nostalgia for a long-lost tropical Eden. Resurrecting the fascinating history of plant prospecting in the tropics, from the colonial era to the present day, The Ethnobotany of Eden rewrites with modern science the degradation narrative we’ve built up around tropical forests, revealing the entangled origins of our fables of forest cures.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEthnobotanyzTropics. 0aEthnobotany-Tropics. 0aTraditional medicinezTropics. 0aTraditional medicine-Tropics. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh  aAfrican diaspora.  aTorrid Zone.  acolonial period.  acultural erosion.  aenvironmental narrative.  aethnobotany.  agender.  amedicinal plants.  atropical rainforest.  aweeds.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226547855423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226547855/original  a978-3-11-068858-0  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles